Running as non-root.

There are two places to set the user. The first is in the dockerfile. You do the steps that need root, like installing packages, then create a dedicated system user, then switch to it with the user instruction, and then set the command. A few best practices apply. Create a purpose-built system user for the app rather than reusing the generic nobody account, which distros treat inconsistently. Pick a high user-I-D that will not collide with common host user-I-Ds. And place the user instruction after everything that needs root, because switching too early forces awkward privilege patterns in your build steps.

The second place is at run time, with a user flag that overrides the image's user, taking a user-I-D and optionally a group-I-D. Running the container as your own host user is the standard fix for the bind-mount file-ownership problem from notebook four, because then the files it creates carry your host ownership rather than root's.

Sometimes an image insists on running as root, like a web server that wants to bind a low port, or a database for certain operations. There are three good responses. You can map the port, running the service as non-root on a high port inside the container and publishing it to a low host port, so the privilege lives on the host side rather than in the container. You can use a non-root variant of the image, since many official images have unprivileged cousins. Or you can grant only the single capability the process actually needs, like the one that lets a non-root process bind low ports, rather than handing it full root.
